photo.title: Telegraph Hill

description._content:
I'm not one to meticulously plan out an experience ahead of time, so I let the flow of traffic carry me into the city.  Somehow I ended up on Russian Hill (as I found out later) and against all odds found a FREE parking spot on Chestnut Street!  It was a wonderful area to walk with Blanca in the city as it's a classy residential neighborhood and there are wide sidewalks with relatively few people, some trees and wonderful views in every direction!  

Blanca was fantastic and patiently walked and stopped and turned with me like my shadow.  The only thing she objected to was stepping over the tracks for the cable cars.  They were vibrating slightly and making sounds even with no cable car in sight, and after stepping over them twice against her better judgment, I could take a hint and avoided asking her to do it a third time.

This is on Francisco Street looking towards Telegraph Hill with Coit Tower at the top.

photo.title: Christmas Gift

description._content: Zack and I have a Christmas tradition to wake up at the wee hours of the night on Christmas Morning and drive to San Francisco to photograph the sunrise. It started a number of years ago, before I had family obligations, partially because I don't celebrate Christmas and partially because Zack was away from his family. Regardless, we've done this for about 6 years now and it's a fun little tradition (minus being super sleepy). Looking at the weather forecast, I wasn't quite sure where we should head this year. We'd done the Golden Gate Bridge, we'd photographed the Bay Bridge, we'd been to the ferry building ... most of the iconic SF photos had been done. Fortunately, the decision was made very easy when I woke up at 4am and checked Escaype (our favorite sunrise forecasting app) and it said "HEAD TO THE GOLDEN GATE BRIDGE." Despite Zack being a few minutes late, we arrived at the Golden Gate Bridge quite early. Looking at the clouds, I knew we needed to be close to the bridge ... the views from Hawk Hill would have had too much empty sky. Battery Spencer became our go-to spot. Here we ran into another photographer, a visitor to SF, Eddy Lin, who asked to tag alone. We were in for a treat, the sunrise pre-burn was absolutely *stunning*. I find the Golden Gate Bridge looks its best during Blue Hour, when the bridge is still lit up, the lights are on and visible in the city, and the sky is still mostly blue, with a star or two to be found left in the sky. Sure enough, the entire cloud system lit up like an explosion and we snapped away for a good 20 minutes. Once it burned out I packed up my gear and walked back to the car and took a pit-stop at the bathroom. When I walked out the door I realized the sky was on fire again. Grabbing our gear we raced back to the bridge and took a few iPhone snaps, by now the sun was coming up and the real burn was on, but with the city and the bridge lights washed out, I didn't even bother with the real camera. photo.title: California Industrial Scenes

description._content:
Coit Tower is a famous San Francisco landmark which opened in 1933. The Tower’s namesake - wealthy socialite Lillie Hitchcock Coit - seemed to have a thing for firemen and followed Knickerbocker Engine Company No. 5 to fires from age 15 onward, finally being awarded the status of honorary member of the company in 1863. After her death in 1929 she left a third of her fortune to the city and this was used to build a memorial to her and to the firemen of San Francisco – Coit Tower.  

From the San Francisco Parks and Rec Site : “The murals inside the tower’s base were painted in 1934 by a group of artists employed by the Public Works of Art Project, a precursor to the Works Progress Administration (WPA), and depict life in California during the Depression. When violence broke out during the 1934 longshoremen’s strike, controversy over the radical content in some of the panels became quite heated. Some of the most controversial elements were painted over, and the tower was padlocked for several months before the frescoes were finally opened to the public in the fall of 1934.”

The Mural :
The 10’ X 24’ fresco “California Industrial Scenes” by John Langley Howard. This one is full of details, a band of rather grim looking workers, scenes of hydraulic and hard rock mining, hydroelectric power, gold panning, sluicing and dredging. A hobo encampment appears to be visited by some well heeled city slickers. Being draped over bathrooms and front entrance I lost some additional scenes of the oil industry. 
3 images stitched in lightroom6

photo.title: Crookedest Street

description._content:
Cars traverse down San Francisco's Russian Hill along the famous block of switchbacks of Lombard Street between Hyde and Leavenworth, dubbed "the crookedest street in the world", as a full moon rises behind Telegraph Hill and the Bay Bridge.

This shot taken last year from one of our "Night Eyes Photo Workshops" around the city, hosted by me and Matt G. This spot is great fun on a Saturday night when the line of tourists in vehicles is seemingly endless, and an occasional stray car clips the hedgerows...or worse. If you come here to shoot, be alert and know that drunk drivers do not always have complete control of their brakes. Nevertheless, a good time was had by all.

I brought a minimal rig with me, so this was the K5 with the tiny but capable DA21mm Limited lens. One minute exposure in Bulb mode.

Thanks for looking~!

photo.title: Coit Tower on Telegraph Hill

description._content: The skyline of San Francisco features a prominent landmark......Coit Tower.  In 1933 Coit Tower was constructed in Pioneer Park atop Telegraph Hill in San Francisco as a city beautification project, immediately becoming a landmark attracting tourists.  The art deco tower, 210 feet of unpainted reinforced concrete, was designed by architects Arthur Brown, Jr. and Henry Howard.  It was built at the bequest of Lillie Hitchcock Coit who had left one-third of her estate to the City "to be expended in an appropriate manner for the purpose of adding to the beauty of the city which I have always loved".  Contrary to popular opinion, the tower was not designed to resemble a fire hose nozzle. This belief persists in part because of Lillie Hitchcock Coit's affinity with the San Francisco fire fighters of the day.

There's a huge amount of detail tucked away in this panorama - you can even see the sea lion colony if you know where to look! About one-fifth in from the left is Lombard Street, which is in infamous curvy road you've probably seen before. photo.title: San Francisco - Lombard Street

description._content:
Lombard Street in San Francisco is touted as the "crookedest street in the world."  There are, however, streets in San Francisco that are more crooked than Lombard Street.

The street, however, is lovely with its flowerbeds.  It is definitely worth the trip, as you can see by the vista from the top.  You can just make out Coit Tower on the right.

The 'Powell and Hyde Streets' cable car stops at the top of the street.  It is a fun way to travel to the street!

photo.title: Lucien Labaudt's "Powell Street", #2

description._content:
This mural by Lucien Adolphe Labaudt (1880-1943) is located along the walls of a spiral staircase in Coit Tower that is not generally open to the public.  This stunningly detailed mural depicts a street scene on San Francisco's Powell Street and covers both facing sides of a spiral staircase that leads to the second floor of the tower.  Labaudt was also a noted fashion designer hence the detail reflected in the clothing worn by the subjects in this mural.

Labaudt was a native of France who studied in Europe before emigrating to the U.S. in 1906 and finally to San Francisco in 1911.  He had a dressmaking shop on Powell Street and was an artist in his spare time ultimately emerging as one of the West Coast's finest painters.  During World War II he went to Asia as an artist correspondent for Life Magazine and was killed in a plane crash enroute to China from India.  Labaudt's murals are also displayed at the Beach Chalet in San Francisco.
___________________________________________
The "Powell Hotel" (see marquee in upper right corner), built in 1908, was reconstructed in 2014 and renamed the "Axiom Hotel".

photo.title: Industries of California

description._content:
Coit Tower is a famous San Francisco landmark which opened in 1933. The Tower’s namesake - wealthy socialite Lillie Hitchcock Coit - seemed to have a thing for firemen and followed Knickerbocker Engine Company No. 5 to fires from age 15 onward, finally being awarded the status of honorary member of the company in 1863. After her death in 1929 she left a third of her fortune to the city and this was used to build a memorial to her and to the firemen of San Francisco – Coit Tower.  


From the San Francisco Parks and Rec Site : “The murals inside the tower’s base were painted in 1934 by a group of artists employed by the Public Works of Art Project, a precursor to the Works Progress Administration (WPA), and depict life in California during the Depression. When violence broke out during the 1934 longshoremen’s strike, controversy over the radical content in some of the panels became quite heated. Some of the most controversial elements were painted over, and the tower was padlocked for several months before the frescoes were finally opened to the public in the fall of 1934.”

The Mural :
The 10’ X 34’ fresco “Industries of California” by Ralph Stackpole shows industrial scenes of California. Fellow artist including William Hesthal and Helen Clement Mills are included in the scene. Stackpole in turn appears in many other works.

photo.title: City Life

description._content:
Coit Tower is a famous San Francisco landmark which opened in 1933. The Tower’s namesake - wealthy socialite Lillie Hitchcock Coit - seemed to have a thing for firemen and followed Knickerbocker Engine Company No. 5 to fires from age 15 onward, finally being awarded the status of honorary member of the company in 1863. After her death in 1929 she left a third of her fortune to the city and this was used to build a memorial to her and to the firemen of San Francisco – Coit Tower.  

From the San Francisco Parks and Rec Site : “The murals inside the tower’s base were painted in 1934 by a group of artists employed by the Public Works of Art Project, a precursor to the Works Progress Administration (WPA), and depict life in California during the Depression. When violence broke out during the 1934 longshoremen’s strike, controversy over the radical content in some of the panels became quite heated. Some of the most controversial elements were painted over, and the tower was padlocked for several months before the frescoes were finally opened to the public in the fall of 1934.”

The Mural :
The 10’ X 34’ fresco “City Life” was painted by Victor Arnautoff assisted by Edward Hansen and Farwell Taylor. Familiar downtown buildings are portrayed with many details. In the foreground there is a robbery at gunpoint, in the background there is a terrible traffic accident but it looks like Engine Company #5 has got there first. The newspaper stand in the center features the actual Coit Tower ticket booth. Mainstream newspaper and periodicals are on our left while more leftist faire is on the right side. Charlie Chaplin’s city lights is playing at the cinema while a sign directs cars to the Auto Ferry to Oakland in lieu of the Bay Bridge which would not be opened until November 1936.  

Like all the Coit murals the detail is wonderful with so many vignettes of city life squeezed into one sweeping view. My image was made from 6 images stitched in Lightroom6. There is a bit of curvature in the image I couldn’t take out and the ticket booth is blacked out as the attendant was in a rather awkward pose. The morning sun was entering the building causing some difficult contrasts, exposures ranged from 1/100 at the edges to 1/1000 in the center.

photo.title: Coit Tower @ San Francisco

description._content:
Coit Tower, also known as the Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, is a 210-foot (64 m) tower in the Telegraph Hill neighborhood of San Francisco, California. The tower, in the city's Pioneer Park, was built in 1933 using Lillie Hitchcock Coit's bequest to beautify the city of San Francisco; at her death in 1929 Coit left one-third of her estate to the city for civic beautification. The tower was proposed in 1931 as an appropriate use of Coit's gift. It was added to the National Register of Historic Places on January 29, 2008.[1]


The art deco tower, built of unpainted reinforced concrete, was designed by architects Arthur Brown, Jr. and Henry Howard, with fresco murals by 27 different on-site artists and their numerous assistants, plus two additional paintings installed after creation off-site. Although an apocryphal story claims that the tower was designed to resemble a fire hose nozzle[3] due to Coit's affinity with the San Francisco firefighters of the day, the resemblance is coincidental.
